text: another day of protests in Venezuela
demonstrators block the streets with
trash and police respond with teargas
during the day the protests had been
more peaceful though the huge numbers
from both sides who turned out on the
streets of the capital showed just how
divided the country has become more than
two weeks in the demonstrations are seen
as the biggest test yet to the socialist
leader Nicolas Maduro since he took
power last year opposition leader
Henrique Capriles told his supporters to
carry on with the protests but urge them
to avoid violence the opposition blames
the government for food shortages high
inflation and insecurity on the other
side of the city women marched towards
the presidential palace to support mr.
Maduro who accuses the opposition of
trying to organize a coup against him
women of the motherland if one day
because of this imperialist and fascist
violence one day you wake up and Nicolas
Maduro is not president will you
recognize another president
mr. Maduro has been using strong
language over the past few days accusing
Washington of supporting what he called
fascist protesters he has expelled US
diplomats while at the same time urging
US President Obama to hold talks with
his government so far the US response as
not satisfied mr. Maduro nor has it
satisfied the protesters who have vowed
not to leave the streets until he
resigns irina caselli BBC News Caracas
